'''BRICS''' is an [[international organization|intergovernmental organization]] consisting of ten countries—[[Brazil]], [[Russia]], [[India]], [[China]], [[South Africa]], [[Egypt]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Indonesia]], [[Iran]] and the [[United Arab Emirates]].  It is considered to be a counterpart and alternative to the [[G7]] bloc of the world's largest economies and combined represent nearly half<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kurian |first=Oommen C. |last2=Sarkar |first2=Debosmita |last3=Suri |first3=Shoba |date=13 January 2025 |title=The Role of BRICS Leadership in Forging Climate and Health Strategies for a One-Health World |url=https://www.orfonline.org/research/the-role-of-brics-leadership-in-forging-climate-and-health-strategies-for-a-one-health-world |access-date=2025-01-20 |website=[[Observer Research Foundation]] |language=en}}</ref> of the world's population.

The term '[[BRIC]]' was originally identified to highlight investment opportunities.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news |last=Xie |first=Ye |date=8 November 2015 |title=Goldman's BRIC Era Ends as Fund Folds After Years of Losses |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-11-08/goldman-s-bric-era-ends-as-fund-closes-after-years-of-losses |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230131044405/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-11-08/goldman-s-bric-era-ends-as-fund-closes-after-years-of-losses |archive-date=31 January 2023 |access-date=10 November 2022 |work=Bloomberg}}</ref> The multipolar<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Gallagher |first1=Adam |last2=Cheatham |first2=Andrew |date=17 October 2024 |title=What's Driving a Bigger BRICS and What Does it Mean for the U.S.? |url=https://www.usip.org/publications/2024/10/whats-driving-bigger-brics-and-what-does-it-mean-us |access-date=2025-01-15 |website=United States Institute of Peace |language=en |quote=Multipolarity is the first trend that must be considered when thinking about BRICS’ growing relevance.}}</ref> [[List of country groupings|grouping]]<ref>{{Cite web |last=Curtis |first=John |date=11 November 2024 |others=Research Briefing |title=The BRICS group: Overview and recent expansion |url=https://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-10136/CBP-10136.pdf |website=House of Commons Library, UK Parliament |quote=Writing in 2023, Bhaso Ndzendze of the University of Johannesburg observed that the BRICS has “at various points […] has referred to itself as a forum, a platform, a mechanism, a partnership, or a strategic partnership, to name a few”. Professor Ndzendze notes it has been labelled by others as “an alliance or a bloc”.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Ndzendze |first=Bhaso |date=2023-08-24 |title=Brics expansion: six more nations are set to join – what they’re buying into |url=https://theconversatio

