{{Donald Trump series}}
The [[President of the United States]] issues [[executive order]]s (in addition to other [[List of executive actions by Donald Trump|executive actions]]) to help officers and agencies of the executive branch manage the operations within the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] itself.

<onlyinclude>On his first day in office as 47th president, [[Donald Trump|U.S. President Donald Trump]] issued executive orders rescinding many of the [[List of executive actions by Joe Biden|previous administration's executive actions]], [[Withdrawing the United States from the World Health Organization|withdrew the U.S. from the World Health Organization]] and [[United States withdrawals from the Paris Agreement|Paris Agreement]],<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-01-20 |title=Trump signs executive order directing US withdrawal from the Paris climate agreement — again |url=https://apnews.com/article/trump-paris-agreement-climate-change-788907bb89fe307a964be757313cdfb0 |access-date=2025-01-21 |website=AP News |language=en}}</ref> [[Defending Women from Gender Ideology Extremism and Restoring Biological Truth to the Federal Government|rolled back federal recognition]] of any genders outside male and female,<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump rolls back trans and gender-identity rights and takes aim at DEI |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/jan/20/trump-executive-order-gender-sex |access-date=21 January 2025 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> froze new regulations, froze hiring for [[Government employees in the United States|federal workers]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump rolls back trans and gender-identity rights and takes aim at DEI |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/jan/20/trump-executive-order-gender-sex |access-date=21 January 2025 |work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Hiring Freeze |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/2025/01/hiring-freeze |access-date=2025-01-23 |website=whitehouse.gov |language=en-US}}</ref> founded the [[Department of Government Efficiency]], issued an executive order related to government censorship of free speech (largely symbolic due to [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] protections), reversed the withdrawal of [[Cuba]]'s designation as a [[State Sponsors of Terrorism (U.S. list)|state sponsor of terror]], reversed sanctions on [[Israeli settlement|Israeli settlers]], rolled back [[Executive Order 14110|policy on artificial intelligence]], [[Trump administration family separation policy|reversed]] the Family Reunification Task Force,<ref>"The Trump administration revoked a Biden executive order that created a task force to reunify families separated at the southern border. In the time the task force was in place, it reunified nearly 800 children with their parents, according to a report it released last year." [https://www.nytimes.com/live/2025/01/20/us/trump-executive-orders "Live Updates"] ''The New York Times'', January 20, 2025.</ref> issued a [[Pardon of January 6 United States Capitol attack defendants|mass pardon]] of all [[January 6 United States Capitol attack|January 6 rioters]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Trump commutes sentences of Jan. 6 extremist group leaders; Tarrio gets pardon |url=https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/5097034-trump-commutes-jan-6-sentences/ |access-date=21 January 2025 |website=thehill.com |publisher=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-01-21 |title=Trump pardons roughly 1,500 criminal defendants charged in the Jan. 6 Capitol attack |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/amp/rcna187735 |access-date=2025-01-21 |work=NBC News |language=en}}</ref> designated [[Drug cartel#Mexico|Mexican drug cartel]]s as [[United States Department of State list of Foreign Terrorist Organizations|foreign terrorist organizations]], [[Protecting the Meaning and Value of American Citizenship|attempted to end]] [[Birthright citizenship in the United States|birthright citizenship]] for new children of [[Illegal immigration to the United States|undocumented immigrants]], granted [[TikTok]] a 75-day pause before it [[Restrictions on TikTok in the United States|would be banned]], and declared a national emergency on the [[Mexico–United States border|southern border]] that would trigger the deployment of the [[Unit
